    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "# Statistical Inference\n"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": null,
      "metadata": {},
      "outputs": [],
      "source":[
        "alpha = 0.05\n",
        "test_set = cleaned_df['selling_price'].sample(frac=0.2, random_state=420321)  # 20% data sample for normality test\n",
        "print(f\"\\nTest set shape: {len(test_set)} rows and 25 columns.\")\n",
        "print(f\"\\nH0: The distribution of Selling Price is normal.\\nH1: The distribution of Selling Price is not normal.\\nSignificance level (alpha): {alpha}\")\n",
        "\n",
        "# Shapiro-Wilk test for distribution normality\n",
        "\n",
        "shapiro_test = scipy.stats.shapiro(test_set)\n",
        "print(\"\\n--- Shapiro-Wilk Test for normality of Selling Price distribution ---\")\n",
        "print(f\"Test statistic: {shapiro_test.statistic}, p-value: {shapiro_test.pvalue}\")\n",
        "\n",
        "if shapiro_test.pvalue < alpha:\n",
        "    print(\"We reject the null hypothesis: The distribution of Selling Price is not a normal distribution.\")\n",
        "else:\n",
        "    print(\"We do not reject the null hypothesis: The distribution of Selling Price is a normal distribution.\")"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source":[
        "The test result yielded a p-value significantly smaller than 0.05. This means that we have strong grounds to reject the null hypothesis. This implies that the distribution of car prices in the examined dataset is not a normal distribution, which is also confirmed by previous observations from the histogram (strong positive skewness). The violation of the normality assumption can affect the interpretation of significance tests in classical linear regression, but for predictive purposes in machine learning, it is not a critical limitation."
      ]
    },
    {
